[
  {
    "id": 1,
    "text": "This is a loss surface for a simple quadratic function: the loss equals weight squared.",
    "voice": "default",
    "speed": 1.0
  },
  {
    "id": 2,
    "text": "We start at weight w zero equals three, and compute the gradient.",
    "voice": "default",
    "speed": 1.0
  },
  {
    "id": 3,
    "text": "With a normal learning rate of zero point one, gradient descent converges smoothly to the minimum.",
    "voice": "default",
    "speed": 1.0
  },
  {
    "id": 4,
    "text": "Now let's see what happens with an exploding gradient, using a learning rate of one point five, which is much larger than the critical value.",
    "voice": "default",
    "speed": 1.0
  },
  {
    "id": 5,
    "text": "The overshoot is catastrophic! The weights flip to the opposite side with even larger magnitude.",
    "voice": "default",
    "speed": 1.0
  },
  {
    "id": 6,
    "text": "Each update drives the weights further away from the minimum, causing the system to diverge completely.",
    "voice": "default",
    "speed": 1.0
  },
  {
    "id": 7,
    "text": "A large learning rate causes weights to explode, making training impossible.",
    "voice": "default",
    "speed": 1.0
  }
]

